The '''pelvic thrust''' is the thrusting motion of the [[pelvis|pelvic]] region, which is used for a variety of activities, such as dance or [[Human sexual activity|sexual activity]].

==Sexual activity and innuendo==
The pelvic thrust is used during [[sexual intercourse]] by many species of [[mammal]]s,<ref name="Estes1991">{{cite book|author=R. D. Estes|title=The Behavior Guide to African Mammals: Including Hoofed Mammals, Carnivores, Primates|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g977LsZHpcsC&printsec=frontcover#v=snippet&q=copulation%20thrusting&f=false|accessdate=28 July 2013|year=1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-08085-0}}</ref><ref name="Bagemihl1999">{{cite book|author=Bruce Bagemihl|title=Biological Exuberance: Animal Homosexuality and Natural Diversity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5CbRGV8AAIQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=thrusting&f=false|date=15 January 1999|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-19239-6}}</ref><ref name="Dixson2012">{{cite book|author=A. F. Dixson|title=Primate Sexuality: Comparative Studies of the Prosimians, Monkeys, Apes, and Humans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SY-PyKNQglIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=thrusting&f=false|date=26 January 2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-954464-6}}</ref> including humans,<ref name="Kar">{{cite book |authors=Nilamadhab Kar, Gopal Chandra Kar| title = Comprehensive Textbook of Sexual Medicine | publisher = [[Jaypee Brothers| Jaypee Brothers Publishers]]|pages=107–112| isbn = 8180614050|year=2005| accessdate = February 10, 2014 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=YxcjMPbGHQIC&pg=PA107}}</ref> or for other sexual activities (such as [[non-penetrative sex]]).  In 2007, German scientists noted that female monkeys could increase the vigor and amount of pelvic thrusts made by the male by [[Female copulatory vocalizations|shouting during intercourse]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Study Reveals Why Monkeys Shout During Sex|url=http://www.livescience.com/7455-study-reveals-monkeys-shout-sex.html|website=livescience.com|publisher=Charles Q. Choi}}</ref> In [[whitetail deer]], copulation consists of a single pelvic thrust.<ref name="Rue2013">{{cite book|author=Leonard Lee Rue|title=Whitetail Savvy: New Research and Observations about America's Most Popular Big Game Animal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q7AtAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=thrust&f=false|date=3 September 2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|isbn=978-1-62636-531-5}}</ref>

== Dance ==
[[File:Elvis Presley Jailhouse Rock2.jpg|thumb|Elvis Presley performing [[Jailhouse Rock (song)|Jailhouse Rock]]]]
One of the first to perform this move on stage was [[Elvis Presley]], which was quite controversial due to its obvious sexual connotations.  Due to this controversy, he was sometimes shown (as seen on his third appearance on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'') from the waist up on TV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elvisinfonet.com/spotlight_edsullivan.html |title=Welcome to EIN |publisher=Elvisinfonet.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-01}}</ref> Later, the pelvic thrust also became one of the signature moves of [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.businessinsider.in/HappyBirthdayMJ-Top-5-iconic-steps-Michael-Jackson-flooredus-with/articleshow/48743020.cms|title=#HappyBirthdayMJ – Top 5 iconic steps Michael Jackson floored us with|work=[[Business Insider]]| accessdate =3 April 2017}}</ref> [[Twerking]] is also used as a dance move. The sideways pelvic thrust is a famous female dance move in Indian [[Bollywood]] films. Called Thumka, it appears in the lyrics of various songs.

== Infants ==
Pelvic thrusting is observed in infant monkeys, apes, and humans. These observations led ethologist John Bowlby (1969) to suggest that [[child sexuality|infantile sexual behavior]] may be the rule in mammals, not the exception. Thrusting has been observed in humans at eight to 10 months of age and may be an expression of affection. Typically, the infant clings to the parent, then nuzzles, thrusts, and rotates the pelvis for several seconds.<ref>Rathus, Spencer: ''Human sexuality in a world of diversity''  (2007) p. 314</ref>

